    <fr:title text="On bealuwara weorc">On <fr:em><html:span xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" lang="ang">bealuwara weorc</html:span></fr:em></fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Musings</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2022</fr:year>
      <fr:month>12</fr:month>
      <fr:day>1</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>
        <fr:link type="local" href="ericczhao.xml" addr="ericczhao" title="Eric Zhao">Eric Zhao</fr:link>
      </fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>In lines 78-80a of the "<fr:link type="local" href="dreamoftherood.xml" addr="dreamoftherood" title="Dream of the Rood">Dream of the Rood</fr:link>":</fr:p>
    <html:span xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" lang="ang">
      <fr:blockquote>Nu ðu miht gehyran, hæleð min se leofa, 
  <html:br />

  þæt ic bealuwara weorc gebiden hæbbe, 
  <html:br />

  sarra sorga.</fr:blockquote>
    </html:span>
    <fr:p>Roughly modernised, the Cross speaks:</fr:p>
    <fr:blockquote>Now you may hear, my dear warrior, 
  <html:br xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  that I have endured the works of wicked men, 
  <html:br xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  grevious sorrows.</fr:blockquote>
    <fr:p>Here, the neuter acc. <fr:em><html:span xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" lang="ang">weorc</html:span></fr:em> is roughly Mdn.E. "work", and <fr:em><html:span xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" lang="ang">bealuwara</html:span></fr:em><html:span xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" lang="en"><html:span class="sidenote-box"><html:span class="sidenote-number" /><html:span class="sidenote">This is perhaps the pl. gen. of an unrecorded <fr:em><html:span lang="ang">*bealuware</html:span></fr:em>, compounding <fr:em><html:span lang="ang">bealu</html:span></fr:em> ("baleful", "wicked") and <fr:em><html:span lang="ang">ware</html:span></fr:em> ("inhabitant").</html:span></html:span></html:span> has been translated variously as "miscreants", "wicked men". <fr:link type="local" href="bosworth-toller-anglo-saxon-dictionary.xml" addr="bosworth-toller-anglo-saxon-dictionary" title="Bosworth Toller's Anglo-Saxon Dictionary">Bosworth Toller's</fr:link> <fr:link type="external" href="https://bosworthtoller.com/3140">gives</fr:link> "baleful inhabitants", "criminals". But <fr:link type="local" href="britton-1967.xml" addr="britton-1967" title="&quot;Bealuwara Weorc&quot; in the &quot;Dream of the Rood&quot;">apparently</fr:link> this bit has caused philologists some trouble.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Interestingly, it's tempting to compare also "Balrog", which in Sindarin comes from <fr:em>BAL</fr:em> ("power") + <fr:em>raug/rog</fr:em> ("demon") but also seems to echo <fr:em><html:span xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" lang="ang">bealu-wearg</html:span></fr:em> ("outlaw", "wolf") or <fr:em><html:span xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" lang="ang">bealu-broga</html:span></fr:em> ("monster", "terror").</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
